div.font:
Public Subnet - Public facing ALB, Bastion Instance, and NAT gateways reside in this subnet.
Bastion in this subnet is protected by security group and only allows incoming connectivity from
CIDRs from Toyota.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 16px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 102, 204); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

div.font:
Private Subnet - No direct internet access. All internet access is through the NAT gateway instances
in the public subnet. Each DevOps tool will be deployed within these subnets. All traffic must go
through the ALB which is protected using security groups, specific listeners, and specific listener rules
to route traffic to target groups within the private subnets.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 16px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 102, 204); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

div.font:
Availability Zone - The ECS cluster instances and Aurora RDS instances have increased resiliency
by being created in multiple AZs. Each public and private subnet will be created in 3 different AZs.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 16px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 102, 204); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

div.font:
Traffic Flow - TAll traffic flow is depicted with dotted arrows. Ports are specified on the architecture
diagram itself. Most of the DevOps tools will be accessed with HTTPS, so 443 is typically the port
that will be used for end users.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 16px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 102, 204); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

div.font:
AWS Regions - In order to keep SLA's in network location / region outages as well as response times
to clients it is necessary to have multiple regions .
